C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0001.wav|Linda|en|Printing, in the only sense with which we are at present concerned, differs from most if not from all the arts and crafts represented in the Exhibition
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0002.wav|Linda|en|in being comparatively modern.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0003.wav|Linda|en|For although the Chinese took impressions from wood blocks engraved in relief for centuries before the woodcutters of the Netherlands, by a similar process
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0004.wav|Linda|en|produced the block books, which were the immediate predecessors of the true printed book,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0005.wav|Linda|en|the invention of movable metal letters in the middle of the fifteenth century may justly be considered as the invention of the art of printing.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0006.wav|Linda|en|And it is worth mention in passing that, as an example of fine typography,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0007.wav|Linda|en|the earliest book printed with movable types, the Gutenberg, or "forty-two line Bible" of about fourteen fifty-five,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0008.wav|Linda|en|has never been surpassed.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0009.wav|Linda|en|Printing, then, for our purpose, may be considered as the art of making books by means of movable types.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0010.wav|Linda|en|Now, as all books not primarily intended as picture-books consist principally of types composed to form letterpress,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0011.wav|Linda|en|it is of the first importance that the letter used should be fine in form;
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0012.wav|Linda|en|especially as no more time is occupied, or cost incurred, in casting, setting, or printing beautiful letters
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0013.wav|Linda|en|than in the same operations with ugly ones.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0014.wav|Linda|en|And it was a matter of course that in the Middle Ages, when the craftsmen took care that beautiful form should always be a part of their productions whatever they were,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0015.wav|Linda|en|the forms of printed letters should be beautiful, and that their arrangement on the page should be reasonable and a help to the shapeliness of the letters themselves.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0016.wav|Linda|en|The Middle Ages brought calligraphy to perfection, and it was natural therefore
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0017.wav|Linda|en|that the forms of printed letters should follow more or less closely those of the written character, and they followed them very closely.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0018.wav|Linda|en|The first books were printed in black letter, i.e. the letter which was a Gothic development of the ancient Roman character,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0019.wav|Linda|en|and which developed more completely and satisfactorily on the side of the "lower-case" than the capital letters;
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0020.wav|Linda|en|the "lower-case" being in fact invented in the early Middle Ages.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0021.wav|Linda|en|The earliest book printed with movable type, the aforesaid Gutenberg Bible, is printed in letters which are an exact imitation
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0022.wav|Linda|en|of the more formal ecclesiastical writing which obtained at that time; this has since been called "missal type,"
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0023.wav|Linda|en|and was in fact the kind of letter used in the many splendid missals, psalters, etc., produced by printing in the fifteenth century.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0024.wav|Linda|en|But the first Bible actually dated (which also was printed at Maintz by Peter Schoeffer in the year fourteen sixty-two)
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0025.wav|Linda|en|imitates a much freer hand, simpler, rounder, and less spiky, and therefore far pleasanter and easier to read.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0026.wav|Linda|en|On the whole the type of this book may be considered the ne-plus-ultra of Gothic type,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0027.wav|Linda|en|especially as regards the lower-case letters; and type very similar was used during the next fifteen or twenty years not only by Schoeffer,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0028.wav|Linda|en|but by printers in Strasburg, Basle, Paris, Lubeck, and other cities.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0029.wav|Linda|en|But though on the whole, except in Italy, Gothic letter was most often used
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0030.wav|Linda|en|a very few years saw the birth of Roman character not only in Italy, but in Germany and France.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0031.wav|Linda|en|In fourteen sixty-five Sweynheim and Pannartz began printing in the monastery of Subiaco near Rome,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0032.wav|Linda|en|and used an exceedingly beautiful type, which is indeed to look at a transition between Gothic and Roman,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0033.wav|Linda|en|but which must certainly have come from the study of the twelfth or even the eleventh century MSS.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0034.wav|Linda|en|They printed very few books in this type, three only; but in their very first books in Rome, beginning with the year fourteen sixty-eight,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0035.wav|Linda|en|they discarded this for a more completely Roman and far less beautiful letter.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0036.wav|Linda|en|But about the same year Mentelin at Strasburg began to print in a type which is distinctly Roman;
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0037.wav|Linda|en|and the next year Gunther Zeiner at Augsburg followed suit;
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0038.wav|Linda|en|while in fourteen seventy at Paris Udalric Gering and his associates turned out the first books printed in France, also in Roman character.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0039.wav|Linda|en|The Roman type of all these printers is similar in character,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0040.wav|Linda|en|and is very simple and legible, and unaffectedly designed for use; but it is by no means without beauty.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0041.wav|Linda|en|It must be said that it is in no way like the transition type of Subiaco,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0042.wav|Linda|en|and though more Roman than that, yet scarcely more like the complete Roman type of the earliest printers of Rome.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0043.wav|Linda|en|A further development of the Roman letter took place at Venice.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0044.wav|Linda|en|John of Spires and his brother Vindelin, followed by Nicholas Jenson, began to print in that city,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0045.wav|Linda|en|fourteen sixty-nine, fourteen seventy;
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0046.wav|Linda|en|their type is on the lines of the German and French rather than of the Roman printers.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0047.wav|Linda|en|Of Jenson it must be said that he carried the development of Roman type as far as it can go:
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0048.wav|Linda|en|his letter is admirably clear and regular, but at least as beautiful as any other Roman type.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0049.wav|Linda|en|After his death in the "fourteen eighties," or at least by fourteen ninety, printing in Venice had declined very much;
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0050.wav|Linda|en|and though the famous family of Aldus restored its technical excellence, rejecting battered letters,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0051.wav|Linda|en|and paying great attention to the "press work" or actual process of printing,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0052.wav|Linda|en|yet their type is artistically on a much lower level than Jenson's, and in fact
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0053.wav|Linda|en|they must be considered to have ended the age of fine printing in Italy.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0054.wav|Linda|en|Jenson, however, had many contemporaries who used beautiful type,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0055.wav|Linda|en|some of which -- as, e.g., that of Jacobus Rubeus or Jacques le Rouge -- is scarcely distinguishable from his.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0056.wav|Linda|en|It was these great Venetian printers, together with their brethren of Rome, Milan,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0057.wav|Linda|en|Parma, and one or two other cities, who produced the splendid editions of the Classics, which are one of the great glories of the printer's art,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0058.wav|Linda|en|and are worthy representatives of the eager enthusiasm for the revived learning of that epoch. By far,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0059.wav|Linda|en|the greater part of these Italian printers, it should be mentioned, were Germans or Frenchmen, working under the influence of Italian opinion and aims.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0060.wav|Linda|en|It must be understood that through the whole of the fifteenth and the first quarter of the sixteenth centuries
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0061.wav|Linda|en|the Roman letter was used side by side with the Gothic.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0062.wav|Linda|en|Even in Italy most of the theological and law books were printed in Gothic letter,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0063.wav|Linda|en|which was generally more formally Gothic than the printing of the German workmen,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0064.wav|Linda|en|many of whose types, indeed, like that of the Subiaco works, are of a transitional character.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0065.wav|Linda|en|This was notably the case with the early works printed at Ulm, and in a somewhat lesser degree at Augsburg.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0066.wav|Linda|en|In fact Gunther Zeiner's first type (afterwards used by Schussler) is remarkably like the type of the before-mentioned Subiaco books.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0067.wav|Linda|en|In the Low Countries and Cologne, which were very fertile of printed books, Gothic was the favorite.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0068.wav|Linda|en|The characteristic Dutch type, as represented by the excellent printer Gerard Leew, is very pronounced and uncompromising Gothic.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0069.wav|Linda|en|This type was introduced into England by Wynkyn de Worde, Caxton's successor,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0070.wav|Linda|en|and was used there with very little variation all through the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, and indeed into the eighteenth.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0071.wav|Linda|en|Most of Caxton's own types are of an earlier character, though they also much resemble Flemish or Cologne letter.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0072.wav|Linda|en|After the end of the fifteenth century the degradation of printing, especially in Germany and Italy,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0073.wav|Linda|en|went on apace; and by the end of the sixteenth century there was no really beautiful printing done:
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0074.wav|Linda|en|the best, mostly French or Low-Country, was neat and clear, but without any distinction;
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0075.wav|Linda|en|the worst, which perhaps was the English, was a terrible falling-off from the work of the earlier presses;
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0076.wav|Linda|en|and things got worse and worse through the whole of the seventeenth century, so that in the eighteenth printing was very miserably performed.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0077.wav|Linda|en|In England about this time, an attempt was made (notably by Caslon, who started business in London as a type-founder in seventeen twenty)
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0078.wav|Linda|en|to improve the letter in form.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0079.wav|Linda|en|Caslon's type is clear and neat, and fairly well designed;
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0080.wav|Linda|en|he seems to have taken the letter of the Elzevirs of the seventeenth century for his model:
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0081.wav|Linda|en|type cast from his matrices is still in everyday use.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0082.wav|Linda|en|In spite, however, of his praiseworthy efforts, printing had still one last degradation to undergo.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0083.wav|Linda|en|The seventeenth century founts were bad rather negatively than positively.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0084.wav|Linda|en|But for the beauty of the earlier work they might have seemed tolerable.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0085.wav|Linda|en|It was reserved for the founders of the later eighteenth century to produce letters which are positively ugly, and which, it may be added,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0086.wav|Linda|en|are dazzling and unpleasant to the eye owing to the clumsy thickening and vulgar thinning of the lines:
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0087.wav|Linda|en|for the seventeenth-century letters are at least pure and simple in line. The Italian, Bodoni, and the Frenchman, Didot,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0088.wav|Linda|en|were the leaders in this luckless change, though our own Baskerville, who was at work some years before them, went much on the same lines;
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0089.wav|Linda|en|but his letters, though uninteresting and poor, are not nearly so gross and vulgar as those of either the Italian or the Frenchman.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0090.wav|Linda|en|With this change the art of printing touched bottom,
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0091.wav|Linda|en|so far as fine printing is concerned, though paper did not get to its worst till about eighteen forty.
C:/Temp/FYP/LJSpeech-1.1/LJSpeech_Processed/10min/LJ001-0092.wav|Linda|en|The Chiswick press in eighteen forty-four revived Caslon's founts, printing for Messrs. Longman the Diary of Lady Willoughby.
